@Andrzej

Yes, cramp. There are various origin stories for "charley horse", but most seem to involve a lame horse called Charley.
I did some studying of Canadian vocabulary before I went to work in Thunder Bay, but literally the first patient I saw was a young woman who told me she'd had a "charley horse on the chesterfield". She might as well have been speaking Polish...

@Petrol

MAGS would probably have a "for short" marker on it.  But RAGS is a well-known expression for the National Inquirer and other disreputable papers available near most supermarket checkout counters in the US.

As Heathie said, RAGS was instant for me, and MAGS never occurred to me.

@Andrzej

A Charley horse isn't just a cramp.  It's the kind of leg cramp when you're sleeping on it the wrong way and you wake up and feel a piercing pain in your calf muscles, and don't have any idea where that came from.  You tell yourself, turn over gently and slowly relax your muscle.  It calms down, you wait about five minutes in place, and you hope that when you try to stand up, it doesn't come roaring back.  (You can also get a Charley horse from strenuous activity, but the in-bed kind are the cruelest.)

Stomach cramps, for example, are never Charley horses.

@Andrzej

Yes, really just a cramp. The young woman I mentioned got hers during the day, while watching television. Some people get them at night. Sometimes they affect the thigh or the foot instead of the calf. Best management is to get up and put weight on the affected leg, bobbing gently up and down on your toes to stretch the cramped muscle.
They're impressive while they last, but in the UK, as in Poland, they're just "cramp in my leg/foot" rather than having any kind of special name.

@Steve L

